               <entity:description xml:lang="slv"> Prispevek bo obravnaval
                                    zgodovinski razvoj političnih in upravnih puščavskih meja
                                    Jordanije (Transjordanije), pri čemer se bo osredotočil zlasti
                                    na zgodovinsko mejo med današnjima državama Jordanijo in Savdsko
                                    Arabijo. Tema prispevka so dolgoročne posledice ustvarjanja
                                    političnih mejnih črt globoko v redko naseljenem nomadskem
                                    puščavskem prostoru. Preden je bil dosežen dogovor je določanje
                                    meja ad hoc štirideset let povzročalo dvome in nepravilnosti v
                                    nomadski puščavi. V medvojnem obdobju na Bližnjem vzhodu se je
                                    sirska puščava spremenila iz nestalnega in spremenljivega
                                    mejnega območja na robu Osmanskega cesarstva v obmejno pokrajino
                                    z določenimi mejami, razdeljeno med štiri nove različne
                                    nacionalne države, ki so imele vsaka svoj pristop do puščavske
                                    pokrajine in njenih nomadskih prebivalcev. Prispevek pa
                                    zagovarja tezo, da se je dediščina "puščavskih in setvenih
                                    površin" – stara spremenljiva meja med nomadskim in stalno
                                    naseljenim prostorom na Bližnjem vzhodu – ohranila tudi pri
                                    upravnih delitvah v času nove države Transjordanije. </entity:description>
               <entity:description xml:lang="eng"> This paper will discuss
                                    the historical development of the political and administrative
                                    desert borders of (Trans)Jordan, especially focusing on the
                                    historical border between the present day states of Jordan and
                                    Saudi Arabia. The long-term consequences of creating political
                                    borderlines deep into a sparsely populated and nomadic desert
                                    space constitute the topic of this paper. The ad hoc bordering
                                    process produced uncertainties and inaccuracies in the nomadic
                                    desert for 40 years before a solution was reached. During the
                                    interwar years in the Middle East, the Syrian desert was
                                    transformed from a fluid and fluctuating frontier on the edge of
                                    the Ottoman Empire to a borderland region with fixed borderlines
                                    divided between four new and different nation states, each with
                                    their own approach to both the desert region and its nomadic
                                    inhabitants. The paper argues, however, that the legacy of ‘the
                                    desert and the sown’, the old fluctuating frontier between the
                                    nomadic and sedentary space in the Middle East, was continued
                                    through the administrative divisions of the new state of
                                    Transjordan during the mandate period. </entity:description>
            </METS:xmlData>
